Governor Aminu Bello Masari of Katsina State has said the rate of involvement of women in drug abuse is alarming and has negative effect in the upbringing of children. The governor said this while speaking to executive members of the state chapter of National Council of Muslim Youth Organization in his office ahead of their forthcoming conference slated for next month. He however, described the theme for the conference which centred on the fight against drug abuse as very apt and timely, pledging to support the success of the programme. According to him, the rate of involvement of women in drugs is alarming and is affecting the moral upbringing of children in the society, explaining that drugs could affect the foetus in the womb of a pregnant woman before the child is delivered. He added that unfiltered milk of breastfeeding mothers involved in the use of drugs could also make the children grow either unintelligently or with mental retardation. The governor also pleaded with the leadership of NACOMYO in hosting the conference at Umar Musa Yar’adua University (UMYU) to also mobilise other students of tertiary institutions from Hassan Usman Katsina polytechnic, Federal College of Education, Katsina, Al-Qalam University, Katsina as well as students from Secondary Schools in neighbouring UMYU to be part of the event. He also observed that the lectures to be delivered during the conference would be in line with the Islamic doctrines and as such would help to overcome or reduce to the barest minimum the cases of drugs abuse. While reiterating the current efforts of government to overcome the insecurity challenge bedeviling the state, the governor urged the people to separate insecurity and drugs related issues from politics, but to harp on the illiteracy of those perpetrating criminality in the state.